The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Kevin injury worsened during IPL
                                                   CRICKET BRIEFS
                      
	 Kevin injury worsened during IPL
    London: Kevin Pietersen aggravated his Achilles injury during the Indian Premier League in South Africa, according to the assistant coach-cum-physiotherapist of the Royal Challengers Bangalore.         
	Evan Speechly, who plays a dual role with the IPL outfit for which Pietersen plays, revealed that Pietersen had sustained the injury during Englands tour of the West Indies but aggravated it while jogging along a Durban beach during the second edition of the IPL.         
	We knew there was a problem there and we monitored it very carefully, Speechly told a cricket website.         
	ODIs vs Aussies         
	 Calcutta: Guwahati will host the only day match in the one-day series against Australia on November 8 while the other six will be day-night affairs.         
	The Board of Control for Cricket in India announced on Friday that the Australian team would arrive in Delhi on October 21 for a seven-match one day cricket series against India. The visitors will depart on November 12.         
	The itinerary         
	Oct. 21: Australia arrives in Delhi; Oct. 25: 1st ODI in Jaipur (D/N); Oct. 28: 2nd ODI in Nagpur (D/N); Oct. 31: 3rd ODI in Delhi; Nov. 2: 4th ODI in Mohali (D/N); Nov. 5: 5th ODI at Hyderabad (D/N); Nov. 8: 6th ODI in Guwahati; Nov. 11: 7th ODI at Mumbai (D/N).         
	Thomson dig         
	 Melbourne: After calling Ricky Ponting a crap captain, former Australian pacer Jeff Thomson has ridiculed his team as cocky and complacent following its humiliating defeat against England in the second Ashes Test .         
	Thomson described Australias bowling as rubbish and lambasted the team management for keeping Stuart Clark out.         
	NZC contracts         
	 Christchurch: Six New Zealand players, including captain Daniel Vettori, have chosen the national team ahead of the Indian Premier League (IPL) and signed their new contracts for the next season despite a clash between a home series and IPL commitments. Vettori, Brendon McCullum, Kyle Mills, Jacob Oram, Jesse Ryder and Ross Taylor were the ones who signed the contracts.         
	Tanvir for Surrey         
	 Karachi: Pakistans left-arm pacer Sohail Tanvir has been signed up by English county Surrey for the remainder of the ongoing season.         
